{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6401fe08-e1c0-4a0b-b359-ea05ad7c144a","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9**, which supports constructor-based `TestContext` injection and async `[TestInitialize]`.\n\n**Recommended pattern:**\n\n- **Constructor** → sync setup + `TestContext` injection\n- **`[TestInitialize]` returning `Task`** → async setup\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Sync init + TestContext injection via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        _service = new MyService();\n    }\n\n    // Async init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.ConnectAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        var result = await _service.GetDataAsync();\n        Assert.IsNotNull(result);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Constructor injection of `TestContext` replaced the old static property pattern (`public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }`).\n- `[TestInitialize]` runs before each test — return `Task` for async work.\n- Use `[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]` (static) for one-time setup if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c64ee745-a43b-43e3-95e5-95d1a57dc873","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use constructor injection — `TestContext` can be injected via the constructor. The old `[TestInitialize]` property-based approach still works but constructor injection is the modern way.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` or the constructor.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an `async Task` return type (supported in MSTest v2+).\n\nActually, let me be more precise about MSTest 3.x. \n\nSo with MSTest 3.x, I can inject `TestContext` directly through the constructor, use `[TestInitialize]` as an async method if needed, and combine both approaches — constructor for synchronous setup and `[TestInitialize]` for any async initialization work.","outputTokens":580,"requestId":"CFD3:12531F:152AD20:1890FEE:69EC171F"},"id":"91c9f958-8311-410f-a2c0-027513e81827","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:21:47.591Z","parentId":"f9aeb0a9-d249-4c15-b66f-07e85289e854"}
